@startuml Nginx CGI with C++ Hello World
title Nginx Common Gateway Interface (CGI) — Inbound Request → Compile C++ → "Hello World"

skinparam sequenceArrowThickness 2
skinparam BoxPadding 10
skinparam NoteBackgroundColor #FFFACD
skinparam NoteBorderColor #DAA520

actor "Client" as Client

box "Web Server" #LightBlue
    participant "Nginx\n(port 80)" as Nginx
end box

box "OS — CGI Process (per request)" #LightCoral
    participant "g++ Compiler" as Compiler
    participant "hello\n(compiled binary)" as Binary
end box

participant "Filesystem" as FS

Client -> Nginx: GET /cgi-bin/hello HTTP/1.1

note over Nginx
  nginx.conf:
  location /cgi-bin/ {
    root  /var/www;
    fastcgi_pass  unix:/run/fcgiwrap.sock;
  }
end note

Nginx -> FS: locate hello.cpp\n(/var/www/cgi-bin/hello.cpp)
FS --> Nginx: file found

Nginx -> Compiler: spawn process\ng++ /var/www/cgi-bin/hello.cpp -o /tmp/hello
activate Compiler
Compiler -> Compiler: parse & compile\nhello.cpp
Compiler -> FS: write compiled binary\n/tmp/hello
Compiler --> Nginx: exit code 0 (success)
deactivate Compiler

Nginx -> Binary: spawn CGI process\n/tmp/hello
activate Binary

note over Binary
  hello.cpp source:
  ──────────────────────────────
  #include <iostream>
  int main() {
    std::cout << "Content-Type: text/plain\r\n";
    std::cout << "\r\n";
    std::cout << "Hello World\n";
    return 0;
  }
  ──────────────────────────────
  CGI rule: write HTTP headers first,
  then a blank line, then the body.
end note

Binary -> Binary: write to stdout:\n"Content-Type: text/plain\r\n"\n"\r\n"\n"Hello World\n"
Binary --> Nginx: stdout captured\nexit code 0
deactivate Binary
Binary -> Binary: process killed ✗

Nginx -> Nginx: parse CGI stdout\nstatus  → 200 OK\nbody    → "Hello World"
Nginx --> Client: HTTP/1.1 200 OK\nContent-Type: text/plain\n\nHello World

note over Client, FS
  Per-request cost breakdown:
  1. Disk read   — locate hello.cpp
  2. g++ spawn   — compile (~100–500 ms first time)
  3. Binary spawn — run & capture stdout
  4. Process killed after every response

  Practical optimization: pre-compile hello.cpp once
  and skip steps 1–2. Real CGI setups never recompile
  on every request — only run the binary.
end note
@enduml
